<paragraph id="8BC136EA0349FFB35FA8FD896F77FB2D" blockId="10.[151,1437,601,1238]" pageId="10" pageNumber="517">
According to Martins &amp; Galileo (1996), 
<taxonomicName id="4C7E4D690349FFB35D65FD896CE5FD89" authorityName="Lacordaire" authorityYear="1872" box="[602,720,601,626]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="517" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Aerenicini">Aerenicini</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4C7E4D690349FFB35C5CFD896DC5FD89" authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1868" box="[867,1008,601,626]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="517" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Hemilophini">Hemilophini</taxonomicName>
by the eyes coarsely faceted (finely in 
<taxonomicName id="4C7E4D690349FFB35FA8FDAD6F1CFD6D" authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1868" box="[151,297,637,662]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="517" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Hemilophini">Hemilophini</taxonomicName>
), and lower eye lobes much longer than gena (at most, slightly longer than gena in 
<taxonomicName id="4C7E4D690349FFB35BFCFDAD6B63FD6D" authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1868" box="[1219,1366,637,662]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="517" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Hemilophini">Hemilophini</taxonomicName>
). Also according to them, Lacordaire separated these tribes based on head: retractile in 
<taxonomicName id="4C7E4D690349FFB35B75FD716AEFFD41" authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1868" box="[1098,1242,673,698]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="517" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Hemilophini">Hemilophini</taxonomicName>
, not retractile in 
<taxonomicName id="4C7E4D690349FFB35FA8FD156F24FD25" authorityName="Lacordaire" authorityYear="1872" box="[151,273,709,734]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="517" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Aerenicini">Aerenicini</taxonomicName>
. We agree that these separation proposed by Lacordaire is not good and, not rare, entirely false. Galileo &amp; Martins (1996) reported that 
<taxonomicName id="4C7E4D690349FFB35EC3FD396CD4FCF9" authority="Lane, 1970" authorityName="Lane" authorityYear="1970" box="[508,737,745,770]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Tacocha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="517" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90AEAF80349FFB35EC3FD396C6FFCF9" box="[508,602,745,770]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="517">Tacocha</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFEF4B1B0349FFB35D5DFD3A6CD4FCF9" author="Lane, F." box="[610,737,746,770]" pageId="10" pageNumber="517" pagination="369 - 428" refId="ref11436" refString="Lane, F. (1970) Cerambycoidea Neotropica nova VII (Coleoptera). Studia Entomologica, 13 (1 - 4), 369 - 428." type="journal article" year="1970">Lane, 1970</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(described in 
<taxonomicName id="4C7E4D690349FFB35CBCFD396A27FCF9" authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1868" box="[899,1042,745,770]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="517" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Hemilophini">Hemilophini</taxonomicName>
) (= 
<taxonomicName id="4C7E4D690349FFB35B7DFD396BADFCF9" authority="Tippmann, 1960" authorityName="Tippmann" authorityYear="1960" box="[1090,1432,745,770]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Phoebemima" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="517" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90AEAF80349FFB35B7DFD396AE1FCF9" box="[1090,1236,745,770]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="517">Phoebemima</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFEF4B1B0349FFB35BE3FD396BADFCF9" author="Tippmann, F. F." box="[1244,1432,745,770]" pageId="10" pageNumber="517" pagination="82 - 217" refId="ref12153" refString="Tippmann, F. F. (1960) Studien uber neotropische Longicornier III (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae). Koleopterologische Rundschau, 37 - 38, 82 - 217." type="journal article" year="1960">Tippmann, 1960</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, described in 
<taxonomicName id="4C7E4D690349FFB35E16FCDD6F8DFCDD" authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1868" box="[297,440,781,806]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="517" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Hemilophini">Hemilophini</taxonomicName>
) differs from the other genera of 
<taxonomicName id="4C7E4D690349FFB35C07FCDD6DF3FCDD" authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1868" box="[824,966,781,806]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="517" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Hemilophini">Hemilophini</taxonomicName>
without humeral carina by the lower eye lobes larger than gena and distance between upper eye lobes equal to width a upper lobe [this is not true, since the distance between upper eye lobes in 
<taxonomicName id="4C7E4D690349FFB35D08FC856CFCFC95" authorityName="Tippmann" authorityYear="1960" box="[567,713,853,878]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Phoebemima" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="517" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90AEAF80349FFB35D08FC856CFCFC95" box="[567,713,853,878]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="517">Phoebemima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be notably wider than a lobe as, for example, in 
<taxonomicName id="4C7E4D690349FFB35A1AFC866F65FC69" authority="Tippmann, 1960" authorityName="Tippmann" authorityYear="1960" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Phoebemima" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="517" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ensifera">
<emphasis id="B90AEAF80349FFB35A1AFC866BA9FC95" box="[1317,1436,854,878]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="517">P. ensifera</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFEF4B1B0349FFB35FA8FCA96F65FC69" author="Tippmann, F. F." box="[151,336,889,914]" pageId="10" pageNumber="517" pagination="82 - 217" refId="ref12153" refString="Tippmann, F. F. (1960) Studien uber neotropische Longicornier III (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae). Koleopterologische Rundschau, 37 - 38, 82 - 217." type="journal article" year="1960">Tippmann, 1960</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
– 
<typeStatus id="54C588480349FFB35E50FCAA6FAAFC69" box="[367,415,890,914]" pageId="10" pageNumber="517">type</typeStatus>
species of the genus]. Also according to them, by this set of features, 
<taxonomicName id="4C7E4D690349FFB35BFAFCA96B16FC69" authorityName="Lane" authorityYear="1970" box="[1221,1315,889,914]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Tacocha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="517" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90AEAF80349FFB35BFAFCA96B16FC69" box="[1221,1315,889,914]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="517">Tacocha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resembles 
<taxonomicName id="4C7E4D690349FFB35FA8FC4D6F86FC4D" authority="Lane, 1976" authorityName="Lane" authorityYear="1976" box="[151,435,925,950]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Melzaerenica" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="517" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90AEAF80349FFB35FA8FC4D6F1AFC4D" box="[151,303,925,950]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="517">Melzaerenica</emphasis>
Lane, 1976
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="4C7E4D690349FFB35EFDFC4D6C0AFC4D" authorityName="Lacordaire" authorityYear="1872" box="[450,575,925,950]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="517" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Aerenicini">Aerenicini</taxonomicName>
). However, the authors did not report why 
<taxonomicName id="4C7E4D690349FFB35B22FC4D6A4DFC4D" authorityName="Lane" authorityYear="1970" box="[1053,1144,925,950]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Tacocha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="517" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90AEAF80349FFB35B22FC4D6A4DFC4D" box="[1053,1144,925,950]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="517">Tacocha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was 
<taxonomicName id="4C7E4D690349FFB35B8BFC4D6B77FC4D" authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1868" box="[1204,1346,925,950]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="517" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Hemilophini">Hemilophini</taxonomicName>
and not 
<taxonomicName id="4C7E4D690349FFB35FA8FC116F24FC21" authorityName="Lacordaire" authorityYear="1872" box="[151,273,961,986]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="517" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Aerenicini">Aerenicini</taxonomicName>
. Comparing the shape of lower eye lobes and also the shape of the ommatidia, it is not possible to understand the placement of 
<taxonomicName id="4C7E4D690349FFB35EE0FC356C44FC05" authorityName="Tippmann" authorityYear="1960" box="[479,625,997,1022]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Phoebemima" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="517" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90AEAF80349FFB35EE0FC356C44FC05" box="[479,625,997,1022]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="517">Phoebemima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<taxonomicName id="4C7E4D690349FFB35DA8FC356D12FC05" authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1868" box="[663,807,997,1022]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="517" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Hemilophini">Hemilophini</taxonomicName>
, since the eyes are not finely faceted and the lower eye lobes are much longer than gena. According to 
<bibRefCitation id="EFEF4B1B0349FFB35DCAFBD96A0AFBD9" author="Martins, U. R. &amp; Galileo, M. H. M." box="[757,1087,1033,1058]" pageId="10" pageNumber="517" pagination="5 - 231" refId="ref11730" refString="Martins, U. R. and Galileo, M. H. M. (2014 a) Subfamilia Lamiinae. Tribo Hemilophini. Parte I. In: Martins, U. R. (Org.), Cerambycidae Sul-Americanos (Coleoptera). Taxonomia. Fol. 13. Sociedade Brasileira de Entomologia, Curitiba, pp. 5 - 231." type="book chapter" year="2014">Martins &amp; Galileo (2014a)</bibRefCitation>
, when defining 
<taxonomicName id="4C7E4D690349FFB35A30FBD96BA9FBD9" authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1868" box="[1295,1436,1033,1058]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="517" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Hemilophini">Hemilophini</taxonomicName>
(translated): “The eyes are finely faceted in nearly all species. In some species (for example, 
<taxonomicName id="4C7E4D690349FFB35A31FBFD6B57FBBD" box="[1294,1378,1069,1094]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Phoebe" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="517" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90AEAF80349FFB35A31FBFD6B57FBBD" box="[1294,1378,1069,1094]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="517">Phoebe</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) the ommatidia are coarser.” All these problems make the differentiation between 
<taxonomicName id="4C7E4D690349FFB35B6EFB816AF2FB91" authorityName="Lacordaire" authorityYear="1872" box="[1105,1223,1105,1130]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="517" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Aerenicini">Aerenicini</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C7E4D690349FFB35A30FB816BA9FB91" authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1868" box="[1295,1436,1105,1130]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="517" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Hemilophini">Hemilophini</taxonomicName>
practically impossible, which suggests that they are a single tribe. However, for the time being, it is much more coherent to transfer 
<taxonomicName id="4C7E4D690349FFB35E4AFB496C32FB49" authorityName="Tippmann" authorityYear="1960" box="[373,519,1177,1202]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Phoebemima" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="517" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90AEAF80349FFB35E4AFB496C32FB49" box="[373,519,1177,1202]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="517">Phoebemima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to 
<taxonomicName id="4C7E4D690349FFB35D15FB496C95FB49" authorityName="Lacordaire" authorityYear="1872" box="[554,672,1177,1202]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="517" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Aerenicini">Aerenicini</taxonomicName>
than maintain it in 
<taxonomicName id="4C7E4D690349FFB35C48FB496A3DFB49" authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1868" box="[887,1032,1177,1202]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="517" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Hemilophini">Hemilophini</taxonomicName>
, following the concept of Martins &amp; Galileo (1996).
</paragraph>
